The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic since this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing – a virtual operator that obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
As the Czech operators belong to the most dear ones in Europe, we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end ČTú also confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularising roaming rates, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of mobile operators in the Czech Republic SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic be kept so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really like to start the fight .
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and covering highly above 100 %.
Instead, mobile telephony operators like to launder the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the chief of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTú) , Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network has no longer likely many possibilities. (However, it might be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time even before the entrance of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile in the market, similar voices were heard in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for operators like this and that they can really succeed.
Finally, for examples, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year this operator has managed to conquer more than 100,000 customers and to become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to actually function, it is enough for many less customers than a traditional operator.
They do not lead to relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the services most restricted
So for example Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move, even the bet on a bet-group not very soon.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not have many expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will rather happen in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman of the Penta Financial Group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything because they do not create any potential competitors.
For some time now, he has not hidden his interest in the launch of a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And first you get better is.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl group.
So maybe better times will come.
From unofficial information it appears that the first virtual operator will have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for creating a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Section of Telefonika O2.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
The press spokesman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová added in a rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "For now we have not noticed any vital and advantageous commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we must already have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates his attention rather than achieving his applications for the 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of the sharing of expenditure and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile telephony operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices, thereby reducing profits.
Why, then, facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The discomforts around the creation U:fon testify that when operators hold to something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure imposed on ČTÚ during the creation period of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from the ČTú web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which you do not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The competitive environment of the mobile telephony market has been poorly enhanced in addition with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would focus on him and above all on his high-ranking services."
However, the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not only the attitude of ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in the economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, this with regard to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the rental contract of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been completed.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, Section for External Relations UOHS, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not be surprising.
On the other hand, the office which needs to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, to take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than a delicate deal.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their market entry has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to UOHS’ interests.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is on its own.
Equally as the same price of petrol for all petrol is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no sign of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking by the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is an analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by ČTú, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - at the end of the accounts logically - the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators do so oddly similar.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which UOHS is kept out of the way.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTú's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This is something UOHS representatives need to know more than good, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it, when no one's watching
While we do not realize that these pseudo-virtual operators still operate, some of them even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephone services which are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the persons pre-established.
Magic is the fact that the company against the operator figures as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
"If the cases you are discussing, of which we will be interested, could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of the persons responsible for mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the case of the 3 companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
No operator at the same time defends himself from such an attitude.
From the activities of these companies they bring a non-differentiating profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a little bit weird at ČTú.
In addition, another issue is being raised for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has rights strong enough to expose similar activities and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As the text has already been mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a significant reduction in prices for services.
At the same time practically in all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were practically identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened in defence, not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and he joined others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators launch the whole case from one to the other as a boiling potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw away the sponge.
If the information of the backstage is right and the virtual operator will really appear from us, the Czech mobile phone market will get back in motion.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly UOHS could remain impossible to the refusal (discrimination) of the other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the day of recognition of the Czech State presented in a solemn manner the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov mëj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the national theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, choir step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem's revisions are Otakar Jeremias and Jaroslav Krček.
On iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already before he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the choir, have a clear saying, that the text is well understandable, that it is in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov męj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divad it in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
He has acquired popularity and people have spontaneously made it his own.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of the Czechoslovakia of 1918 became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
