Some children speak during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most one gets scared, but in fact it doesn't matter much.
It is a benign alternation of sleep called sleep sleep.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have said that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadicly (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason why this phenomenon can be explained.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (make the pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above can be associated with very high stages of fever, stress or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not yet been studied.
Even the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that happens the contrary (scream, scream, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a way out of the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. if coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child excessively before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once sleepwalkers show up trying to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
