The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, since Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the virus of acquired immunodeficiency (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still believed in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to our continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proud that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells him that it has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we didn't know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, that when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been demonstrated that this disease has no doubt been transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique appeared on the market for the identification of HIV: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors to be recognized directly and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used up to then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, since the person has contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus not being able to identify them has decreased so considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years to find a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion.
I believe that today we can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Hema-Québec leadership.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant", Dr. Décary continued before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Necessaries increase as the population ages.
Since cancer is the most aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's population acceptable as donors."
All healthy people who have reached 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is spread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to keep an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of poverty are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, the Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye cells and skin heart valves that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is abundant blood rich in stem cells that can help cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth cordon blood sample and we plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of taking cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access you", because Héma-Québec lacks the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
