In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter by Patrick J. Garver, Vice-President of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest auriferous company has waged a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house that is castrated with the intention of starting a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation dispute, but the law.
Without any surprise, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his.
The outcome of the process is scarce, the writers and editor of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a substantial amount of money in order to organize their own defence and fight, with a decidedly odd weapon, against an army of lawyers funded by practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
In other words, in these arms struggles I learn, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation which would boost his opposition and frighten anyone who is again trying to take a decision on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it's in front of the public that he should have presented his own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates usually take place with the exchange of opinions and not with manganese strikes.
It would therefore be sufficient for the company to open its books, documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the issue.
