The intelligent machine mimics the flying of the skull
What could be the best way to develop anti-collition technologies if not to imitate the sensors of the obstacles in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the surprising project presented to CEATEC in Japan the Calabrians gave the initial strategic direction to the Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collition systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo the Nissan built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized mini-auto with the properties of the bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system able to scan all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technology sector and research and development.
Important is the role of the ape view, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have attracted the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the ape view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters distance within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the ape, changes immediately direction by rotating the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance exercise, unlike the current system, is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
"If it weren't like this, the robot car wouldn't react fast to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot auto project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful layer and more internal than the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes a bee to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in an eyebrow.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go upwards or downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
Instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is fed by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with a high energy density, which means that their duration is higher than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh it is important the instantness of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions which, they predict to Nissan, can be installed on the standard vehicles within 10 years.
Additional application possibilities can be represented by unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leading to destination.
