Mp3 readers on charge, putting the hearing at risk
Listening to high volume music for an extended period of time using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a communication in Brussels refers to the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identifyed Health Risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific opinion - it is read in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour per day holding the high volume device risk a permanent loss of hearing ability".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at high levels can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - the EU responsible continues - there is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters the most, we need to raise the awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion in order to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - the EU executive concludes - confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related equipment".
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about the hearing damage that may result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these damage by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the European Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours a week exceeds the current limits of maximum noise permitted at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under these conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would cover 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
