The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already emerged a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
There is a confirmation in the New York Times of yesterday informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking up the Republican Party, increasingly divided among its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, instead conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the States of the Centre and the South.
The soul, for the most part, made itself prepotently alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just mentioned, however, is just one example of the changes, of the major changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps predestins or already leaves to be seen: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
Both in the USA and in Europe the crisis seems to function as an incubator of incubator phenomena for a long time that in the new climate solidifies and finally comes to light.
The first of these phenomena is the revitalization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of state-sovereignity in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of financial-banking institutions which have, yes, close links with abroad, but which first of all are very broadly involved in the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
What immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In other words, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of play or not to have much to say: the overwhelming proof is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies cannot decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the close it is only the States that own the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in sixth.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market or international organization may possibly ever have similar resources.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from a hint that our future would have to deal more and more with those very little immaterial things that are water, harvests, oil.
All things that, look at a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but are however bound in an absolute way to a restricted space, to a territory.
As for those who are to be sovereign, he certainly owns several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without harvests, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which predicts a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective needs authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, turned out to be so inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And together something even deeper and in a certain disturbing sense: a discredit, an inoffence, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, it seems to be getting more and more on the road, in large areas of the population, to believe that before their actions are the same as the ideas of the social elites so far, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly foreign to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimation of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolutional" elections or in the sudden events of the collective moods of recent and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Baviera to the collapse of Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congresses against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy there is something to do).
It is felt that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what has not since taken shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, potentially stirring up.
In the face of all this talk of a 'rebellion of the masses' on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open for sure is not for nothing.
