The figures provided by the Anec, the main association of the practitioners, speak clearly: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and paying the highest discount are mainly the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinema monosala persi, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to show that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-sala cinemas: 195 additional screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally", notes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec," it is useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for the public sector: the state's pre-debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about the closures, has decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between Comune and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote monosala cinemas both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the proposed rules are tax relief measures for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for stopping and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counter the excess of the multiplex traditional rooms, the quality of the sound and the image must also be improved, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise Cinema", which I had thought of for 10 years already.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto or the Quirinale of via Nazionale now closed, there where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the signs blackened by the dust I turn on the other side".
